---
import ContentLayout from '../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
export const prerender = true;

const faqItems = [
  {
    q: "Is Hawaiian coffee a good gift for non-coffee drinkers?",
    a: "Yes, for two reasons. The recipient does not need to be a connoisseur to recognize Kona as premium. And Hawaiian coffees skew toward smooth, balanced, low-acid profiles (caramel, milk chocolate, light nuttiness) rather than the bright, polarizing fruit notes you find in Ethiopian or Kenyan beans. A casual coffee drinker is far more likely to enjoy a cup of Kona than a Yirgacheffe."
  },
  {
    q: "How much does real Hawaiian coffee cost as a gift?",
    a: "Expect $40 to $60 for a quality 7 oz to 8 oz bag of 100% Kona, $60 to $90 for Extra Fancy grade or peaberry, and $90 to $140 for a multi-region Hawaiian sampler. Anything labeled '10% Kona blend' for $20 is not a real Hawaiian gift; 90% of that bag is mainland or South American coffee with a Hawaiian label."
  },
  {
    q: "Will the coffee still be fresh after shipping?",
    a: "If you order whole bean from a Hawaiian roaster that roasts to order (Koa Coffee does), the bag ships within days of roasting and arrives in 3 to 7 days. That puts it in your recipient's hands well inside the peak 2-to-4-week flavor window. Pre-ground coffee loses freshness faster, so default to whole bean unless you know the recipient does not have a grinder."
  },
  {
    q: "Can I include a card or gift message?",
    a: "Yes. Most Hawaiian roasters that ship direct (Koa included) offer a gift-message field at checkout and ship in branded packaging suitable for gifting. A short handwritten note explaining that the coffee is 100% Hawaiian (not a blend) adds real value, since most recipients do not know the difference and that context turns a nice bag of coffee into a memorable gift."
  },
  {
    q: "Do I have to buy 100% Kona, or are blends okay?",
    a: "For gifting, always buy 100% Kona or 100% Hawaiian. The legal minimum for a '10% Kona blend' label is 10% Kona by weight, which means the recipient is getting mostly generic coffee in a Hawaiian-branded bag. The whole point of a Hawaiian coffee gift is the geographic specificity, and a blend dilutes that to near zero."
  },
  {
    q: "How do I know if Hawaiian coffee is fresh?",
    a: "Look for a roast date printed on the bag (not a 'best by' date, which is meaningless). Coffee is at peak flavor 4 to 21 days after roasting. Reputable Hawaiian roasters print the roast date and ship within a week of roasting. If the bag has no roast date or only a 'best by' stamp 12 months out, it is likely commodity coffee, not a gift-grade single origin."
  }
];

