<h2 class="section-head">How to ship Hawaiian coffee <em>correctly</em></h2>

<p class="body">A few shipping mechanics matter more for Hawaiian coffee than for mainland-roasted coffee, because the package starts its journey in Hawaii.</p>

<ul class="body-list">
  <li><strong>Order at least 2 to 3 weeks ahead.</strong> The coffee needs to arrive fresh and ahead of the gift occasion. Holiday shipping windows can stretch transit times; do not cut it close in December.</li>
  <li><strong>Expect 3 to 7 days of transit to the mainland.</strong> Koa ships from Hawaii by air. Most U.S. addresses see delivery in under a week, but Alaska, Hawaii local, and rural addresses can run longer.</li>
  <li><strong>Whole bean keeps better in transit.</strong> Ground coffee starts losing aromatic compounds the moment it is ground. Whole-bean Hawaiian coffee can sit sealed in the gift box for 2-3 weeks and still brew beautifully when opened. Pre-ground has a shorter window.</li>
  <li><strong>Use the gift-message field at checkout.</strong> Most Hawaiian roasters offer a printed card or note option. Even a single line ('100% Kona, the real thing, enjoy') adds value.</li>
</ul>

<p class="body">For a deeper dive into how to evaluate the coffee itself once it arrives, our <a href="/learn/kona-coffee-grades" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none;">guide to Kona coffee grades</a> covers what Extra Fancy, Fancy, peaberry, and prime actually mean on the bag. And if the recipient becomes a Hawaiian coffee fan and asks you for follow-up picks, the <a href="/learn/best-kona-coffee" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none;">best Kona coffee roundup</a> is the next logical bookmark to send them.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p>The single biggest mistake in Hawaiian coffee gifting: buying a $20 'Kona blend' from a grocery store because the bag looks Hawaiian. By federal labeling rules, that bag is allowed to be 10% Kona by weight, which means the recipient is getting 90% generic coffee with a Hawaiian-themed wrapper. Always buy 100% Kona or 100% Hawaiian from a direct-from-Hawaii roaster.</p>
</div>

